    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Thanks for the response @Haroenv. Well the benefit of being able to use a dictionary rather than an array is extending its usability which also eliminates the need for a loop when it comes to using them in the template. Unless there is an easier way to know whether `attributesToDisplay` contains `title` for example which seems to be a handlebars shortcoming. Consider this usage:\r\n\r\n```html\r\n{{#if attributesToDisplay.title}}\r\n{{#if attributesToDisplay.title.href}}\r\n<a class=\"text-decoration-none\" href=\"\\{{attributesToDisplay.title.href}}\">{{attributesToDisplay.title}}</a>\r\n{{/if}}\r\n{{/if}}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe attributesForFaceting seems to tolerate non-array structures:\r\n\r\n```javascript\r\n{\r\n    attributesForFaceting:\r\n        Array.isArray(combinedAnswers.attributesForFaceting) &&\r\n        combinedAnswers.attributesForFaceting.filter(\r\n            (attribute) => attribute !== 'ais.dynamicWidgets'\r\n        ),\r\n}\r\n```",
